WEBVTT

00:00.960 --> 00:03.507
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:03.507 --> 00:05.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:05.512 --> 00:07.891
<i>ANNIE:</i>
<i>We're searchers, you and me.</i>

00:07.891 --> 00:11.231
<i>My dad, your grandpa‐‐</i>
<i>that good old guy‐‐</i>

00:11.231 --> 00:13.736
they don't make men like that,
little love, not anymore.

00:13.736 --> 00:16.115
‐ Annie Wilkes
from Bakersfield, California.

00:16.115 --> 00:17.911
‐ He would say to me,
"Annie..."

00:17.911 --> 00:19.247
[shouting]

00:19.247 --> 00:21.042
"There are two kinds of people
that made America.

00:21.042 --> 00:22.879
Searchers and settlers."

00:22.879 --> 00:24.800
<i>He settled for nothing,</i>
<i>that one.</i>

00:24.800 --> 00:28.306
<i>Now, my ma, she was a settler.</i>

00:28.306 --> 00:30.603
<i>You set her down anywhere</i>
<i>and she would make a home.</i>

00:30.603 --> 00:32.022
<i>She would make it perfect.</i>

00:32.022 --> 00:34.193
And me, well,

00:34.193 --> 00:37.534
<i>I'm kind of a funny</i>
<i>ol' oogy mess of both,</i>

00:37.534 --> 00:39.871
<i>all mixed up sometimes.</i>

00:39.871 --> 00:42.669
<i>I'm a searcher</i>
<i>who just wants to settle‐‐</i>

00:42.669 --> 00:44.506
<i>wants it bad.</i>

00:44.506 --> 00:46.802
Can't seem to find
that Laughing Place

00:46.802 --> 00:48.346
that'll live up to you.

00:48.346 --> 00:50.602
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

00:50.602 --> 00:52.772
[thunder booms]
[panting]

00:52.772 --> 00:55.611
‐ Did you do something, Mom?

00:55.611 --> 00:56.947
<i>[dramatic musical sting]</i>

00:56.947 --> 00:58.784
‐ [haggard breathing]

01:00.997 --> 01:03.209
<i>[bell rings]</i>

01:03.209 --> 01:06.215
<i>[children chattering,</i>
<i>laughing]</i>

01:07.594 --> 01:10.390
<i>[soft eerie music]</i>

01:10.390 --> 01:11.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:13.146 --> 01:17.404
DIEGO:
"No matter how lonely,
everyone has a...

01:17.404 --> 01:19.241
Lagging"?

01:19.241 --> 01:21.454
TEACHER:
Keep going.

01:21.454 --> 01:24.586
DIEGO:
"Brad Rabbit told Brad Fox,

01:24.586 --> 01:29.428
everyone has a laughing place."

01:29.428 --> 01:31.057
TEACHER:
Very good, Diego.

01:31.057 --> 01:32.977
Annie?

01:32.977 --> 01:35.399
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:36.985 --> 01:38.446
STUDENT:
Is she even reading?

01:38.446 --> 01:40.117
[giggles]

01:41.452 --> 01:44.835
[kids whispering, giggling]

01:44.835 --> 01:48.174
‐ "Brad Rabbit knew
it was better to be friends

01:48.174 --> 01:51.640
"than to fight, so he took..."

01:51.640 --> 01:54.061
STUDENT:
Is she reading the right thing?
[giggles]

01:54.061 --> 01:58.779
‐ "Bad Fox and Big Bear
to the Laughing Place,

01:58.779 --> 02:01.492
where they lived there
as animal friends forever.

02:01.492 --> 02:03.455
‐ That's not what it says.

02:03.455 --> 02:07.087
[laughter]

02:08.632 --> 02:10.636
TEACHER:
That's enough.

02:10.636 --> 02:12.932
[bell rings]
STUDENT: She can't read.

02:12.932 --> 02:17.984
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:17.984 --> 02:20.071
[bus exhaust hisses]

02:20.071 --> 02:23.119
[engine rumbling]

02:23.119 --> 02:26.125
[indistinct chatter]

02:26.125 --> 02:30.676
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:30.676 --> 02:33.682
<i>[tense music]</i>

02:33.682 --> 02:35.477
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:35.477 --> 02:37.231
STUDENT:
She's so weird.

02:37.231 --> 02:38.818
‐ Hey, A‐tard.

02:38.818 --> 02:41.949
Animal friends forever.
STUDENT: [laughs]

02:41.949 --> 02:44.955
‐ Bet you can't even read this.

02:44.955 --> 02:47.752
‐ "Ouch, my face."

02:49.840 --> 02:53.012
‐ What are you
tarding about, tard?

02:53.012 --> 02:56.645
[all screaming]

02:56.645 --> 03:00.611
<i>[unhinged violin music]</i>

03:00.611 --> 03:04.368
COUNSELOR:
It's clear to me that we need
further screening for her sake.

03:04.368 --> 03:07.207
CRYSILDA: No, my Annie
is not the problem here‐‐
your cockadoodie school is.

03:07.207 --> 03:10.213
CARL:
You're not sending my girl
to a pen for mental midgets‐‐

03:10.213 --> 03:12.259
COUNSELOR:
This is her third incident.

03:12.259 --> 03:15.307
We're talking about...

03:15.307 --> 03:16.935
pathological behavior.

03:16.935 --> 03:19.566
CARL: Can I‐‐can I just say‐‐
‐ Jiminy, Carl, can you not?

03:19.566 --> 03:22.321
‐ The hell's this?
<i>Brad Rabbit?</i>

03:22.321 --> 03:24.199
‐ Carl, language.
‐ You mean Br'er Rabbit?

03:24.199 --> 03:25.578
This is supposed to be
the Uncle Remus stories?

03:25.578 --> 03:29.001
‐ Yes, that is
a more contemporary edition.

03:29.001 --> 03:32.132
‐ "Politically correct,"
I think, is the term you're
rooting around for there.

03:32.132 --> 03:36.098
Okay, you are feeding her
this‐‐this touchy‐feely
propaganda.

03:36.098 --> 03:38.061
‐ Carl, Christmas.
‐ And she's‐‐she's bored.

03:38.061 --> 03:40.148
‐ I really wish that
you'd let Annie wait outside
while we finish this discussion.

03:40.148 --> 03:43.196
‐ She's not leaving my sight
in this booby‐hatch
you're running.

03:43.196 --> 03:44.699
My Annie's pure,

03:44.699 --> 03:47.997
and this place
is an open sewer.

03:47.997 --> 03:49.501
COUNSELOR:
Mr. and Mrs. Wilkes,

03:49.501 --> 03:52.674
have you considered speaking
to a psychiatrist about Annie?

03:52.674 --> 03:55.053
Because there are many
helpful new medications‐‐

03:55.053 --> 03:57.182
‐ All of you people, you...
[stammers]

03:57.182 --> 03:59.061
You're foisting chemicals
onto children!

03:59.061 --> 04:00.648
CRYSILDA:
We're taking it from here.

04:00.648 --> 04:03.069
We are gonna be responsible
for her entire education!

04:03.069 --> 04:04.572
Can you handle that?

04:04.572 --> 04:06.033
CARL:
We're not gonna know
until we try!

04:06.033 --> 04:08.204
CRYSILDA:
I am not willing to make
the discovery that...

04:08.204 --> 04:09.999
‐ I'm gonna do it, Crysilda,
and it's gonna work.

04:09.999 --> 04:12.421
You'll see, you just have
to sit back and watch.

04:12.421 --> 04:14.091
CRYSILDA:
[scoffs]

04:16.470 --> 04:18.433
CARL: Come on, girl.
Let's go inside.

04:18.433 --> 04:19.519
[car door slams]

04:19.519 --> 04:26.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:29.371 --> 04:31.042
Now.

04:40.519 --> 04:43.776
<i>[gentle music]</i>

04:43.776 --> 04:45.529
Not bad, right?

04:47.407 --> 04:51.290
Up here, we're gonna make you
a real school‐‐

04:51.290 --> 04:53.377
a school of us.

04:53.377 --> 04:56.133
ANNIE: Is there something
wrong with me, Daddy?

04:56.133 --> 04:58.680
‐ What? No.

04:58.680 --> 05:02.270
‐ Is that why I can't
be in a regular school?

05:02.270 --> 05:03.899
<i>CARL:</i>
<i>Annie‐‐</i>

05:03.899 --> 05:05.694
<i>ANNIE:</i>
<i>The kids are so mean,</i>
<i>and the teachers‐‐</i>

05:05.694 --> 05:08.074
<i>they just don't</i>
<i>look at me right.</i>

05:08.074 --> 05:09.994
‐ Annie‐bear,
listen to me, okay?

05:09.994 --> 05:12.792
Do you know the real story
of the Laughing Place?

05:12.792 --> 05:15.548
I'm not talking about
the hippidy‐dippidy kumbaya...

05:15.548 --> 05:17.635
[babbles]
Okay?

05:17.635 --> 05:19.138
I'm talking about
the real story.

05:19.138 --> 05:22.227
Br'er Fox isn't friends
with Br'er Rabbit.

05:22.227 --> 05:25.776
Br'er Fox wants
to eat Br'er Rabbit,

05:25.776 --> 05:28.615
and that is the real world,
Annie‐bear‐‐

05:28.615 --> 05:30.034
killing and eating...

05:30.034 --> 05:32.455
[goofy babbling]
<i>Running and hiding.</i>

05:32.455 --> 05:33.959
<i>But do you know</i>

05:33.959 --> 05:36.756
<i>what smart old Br'er Rabbit</i>
<i>figured out?</i>

05:36.756 --> 05:39.094
Your Laughing Place

05:39.094 --> 05:41.473
is anywhere you say it is.

05:41.473 --> 05:43.436
<i>ANNIE: It is?</i>
<i>CARL: Well, of course it is.</i>

05:43.436 --> 05:44.772
<i>And you know what else?</i>

05:44.772 --> 05:47.194
<i>We're gonna have you</i>
<i>reading in no time.</i>

05:47.194 --> 05:49.323
‐ How, Daddy?

05:49.323 --> 05:51.076
CARL:
I'ma tell you a story.

05:51.076 --> 05:53.456
‐ [gasps]
I love Daddy's stories.

05:53.456 --> 05:56.212
<i>CARL: I got a new story</i>
<i>to tell, Annie‐bear,</i>

05:56.212 --> 05:58.132
<i>and it's‐‐it's so big</i>

05:58.132 --> 06:00.136
that you're gonna have
to help me.

06:00.136 --> 06:02.432
"Down the gullet
of the dead gorge,

06:02.432 --> 06:04.061
"past the Palace Wagon,

06:04.061 --> 06:06.440
"oxen thin and foaming,

06:06.440 --> 06:08.862
"stumbling in ruts, over bones,

06:08.862 --> 06:12.285
"as Prester Jack, gun cradled,

06:12.285 --> 06:16.293
scanned cliff tops
for savages."

06:16.293 --> 06:18.966
‐ This is your new story?

06:18.966 --> 06:20.761
<i>[mellow, brooding music]</i>

06:20.761 --> 06:22.097
‐ It is indeed.

06:22.097 --> 06:24.101
They say that, uh,

06:24.101 --> 06:26.815
Bach's daughters
worked the organ bellows

06:26.815 --> 06:29.403
while he composed.

06:29.403 --> 06:32.785
Well, that is what
we're gonna try.

06:32.785 --> 06:34.831
You see,

06:34.831 --> 06:38.170
I have to have the typewriter
to make my magic‐‐

06:38.170 --> 06:40.341
I‐‐I love those deep keys‐‐

06:40.341 --> 06:42.972
but the modern
publishing world,

06:42.972 --> 06:46.270
they need everything...

06:46.270 --> 06:48.942
on computer.

06:48.942 --> 06:52.490
CRYSILDA:
Carl?

06:52.490 --> 06:56.331
‐ You are gonna type this

06:56.331 --> 06:58.795
into the keyboard.

06:58.795 --> 07:01.341
Every page, word by word.

07:01.341 --> 07:04.014
‐ Oh, Daddy,
I don't know if I can.

07:04.014 --> 07:05.642
CARL:
We're just gonna
set this right here.

07:05.642 --> 07:07.312
‐ Okay.
CARL: What's this
first letter here?

07:07.312 --> 07:10.694
ANNIE:
I don't want to get it wrong,
not a single word.

07:10.694 --> 07:13.282
‐ Oh, Annie‐bear.

07:13.282 --> 07:14.619
<i>Warmer, warmer.</i>

07:14.619 --> 07:16.748
Warmer, warmer, warmer,
hot, hot, hot.

07:16.748 --> 07:18.250
Boom!

07:18.250 --> 07:19.587
You're already getting
the hang of it.

07:19.587 --> 07:21.716
You're gonna be a writer
yourself in no time.

07:21.716 --> 07:23.970
CRYSILDA: Carl!
‐ I'm coming, damn it!

07:27.812 --> 07:29.272
Go ahead and take her
for a dance

07:29.272 --> 07:31.193
and I'll be back with more
pages soon enough, sweetheart.

07:31.193 --> 07:33.197
‐ More pages for who, Daddy?

07:37.665 --> 07:39.794
‐ My number one fan.
ANNIE: [laughs]

07:39.794 --> 07:41.213
‐ [chuckles]

07:41.213 --> 07:44.219
<i>[ominous music]</i>

07:44.219 --> 07:51.233
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:13.235 --> 08:16.241
[distant train horn honking]

08:37.618 --> 08:39.956
<i>JOY:</i>
<i>"Prester Jack, gun cradled,</i>

08:39.956 --> 08:42.252
<i>"scanned cliff tops</i>
<i>for savages.</i>

08:42.252 --> 08:44.882
<i>"He knew they were waiting</i>
<i>for night, craving it.</i>

08:44.882 --> 08:46.426
<i>"A new moon would bring her in</i>

08:46.426 --> 08:48.932
<i>"if their promise held.</i>

08:48.932 --> 08:51.019
<i>"It was a promise</i>
<i>made at noon</i>

08:51.019 --> 08:53.942
<i>"over water</i>
<i>on the Kiplinger Ford.</i>

08:53.942 --> 08:56.238
Annabel kept her word."

08:56.238 --> 08:58.367
Um...

08:58.367 --> 09:02.000
"Prester Jack kept his.

09:02.000 --> 09:04.714
"And every night,

09:04.714 --> 09:07.636
"they met," uh,

09:07.636 --> 09:11.268
"Be‐‐behind the pale‐less..."

09:11.268 --> 09:12.521
‐ Palace.
ANNIE: Uh, palace.

09:12.521 --> 09:15.484
‐ Palace, sweetheart.
ANNIE: "Wagon."

09:15.484 --> 09:19.075
Um, "Stepped out
of their buff...

09:19.075 --> 09:21.371
"buffet‐‐buffalo robes,

09:21.371 --> 09:24.002
"stepped out of their lives.

09:24.002 --> 09:27.926
And the western moon pain‐‐"

09:27.926 --> 09:31.350
[stammering]
Pain?

09:31.350 --> 09:32.895
Paint?
‐ Let me see‐‐

09:32.895 --> 09:35.776
ANNIE: No, no, I got it.
Pain‐‐painted!

09:35.776 --> 09:39.909
"Painted their bodies white."

09:39.909 --> 09:42.038
‐ Do you like it?

09:42.038 --> 09:45.504
‐ Daddy, I love it.
[laughs]

09:45.504 --> 09:47.465
‐ [sighs]

09:47.465 --> 09:49.679
I love hearing my story
in your voice, Annie‐bear.

09:49.679 --> 09:51.683
It just, uh‐‐it makes it real.

09:51.683 --> 09:55.565
So, um, you really like
this version?

09:55.565 --> 09:57.026
Because I made some
pretty big changes.

09:57.026 --> 10:00.282
‐ Oh, I know,
I‐‐I think it's beautiful.

10:00.282 --> 10:01.994
[lighter flicks]

10:01.994 --> 10:04.709
Especially Annabel.

10:04.709 --> 10:07.756
I hope she leaves McCall
for Prester Jack.

10:07.756 --> 10:08.842
‐ Oh, yeah?

10:08.842 --> 10:11.221
ANNIE: Well, you know,
McCall is awful.

10:11.221 --> 10:13.016
He cheats.
I‐‐I want to hate him.

10:13.016 --> 10:14.687
He's better to hate.

10:14.687 --> 10:17.483
‐ [stammering]
You know, the thing is,
he's complicated, McCall.

10:17.483 --> 10:18.737
That's what makes him
interesting.

10:18.737 --> 10:21.241
‐ Well, bad doesn't
make you interesting.

10:21.241 --> 10:25.082
Mama always says,
"It just makes you bad."

10:25.082 --> 10:27.295
‐ [sighs] Well,

10:27.295 --> 10:30.468
we're not all one thing,
Annie‐bear.

10:30.468 --> 10:32.765
We're all good.
We're all bad.

10:32.765 --> 10:36.522
‐ No, I say you make
McCall worse than he is now

10:36.522 --> 10:37.941
so then we know
who to root for.

10:37.941 --> 10:39.612
‐ You should help your mom.

10:39.612 --> 10:43.243
‐ Oh, I‐‐I can get that, Mom.

10:43.243 --> 10:45.331
CRYSILDA:
Thank you, little love.

10:49.965 --> 10:52.053
There's a couple more bags
in the car.

10:52.053 --> 10:54.474
‐ Okey‐doke.

10:54.474 --> 10:55.685
CRYSILDA:
[sighs]

11:00.946 --> 11:02.825
[sighs]

11:02.825 --> 11:04.494
[grumbles]

11:09.045 --> 11:11.007
[sighs]

11:15.349 --> 11:17.019
Ugh.

11:18.898 --> 11:21.236
No more smoking in the house.

11:21.236 --> 11:24.284
‐ I know.

11:24.284 --> 11:25.620
[cup clatters]

11:27.415 --> 11:29.712
CRYSILDA:
She gonna be ready for the GED?

11:29.712 --> 11:31.381
‐ Girl thinks
like a chess master.

11:31.381 --> 11:32.801
She's always three moves ahead.

11:32.801 --> 11:34.763
‐ Ain't her math
I'm worried about.

11:34.763 --> 11:36.308
ANNIE:
Mama?

11:36.308 --> 11:39.314
Did we go back to alphabetical
order for the pantry?

11:41.401 --> 11:43.656
‐ Why don't you read
for me, Annie?

11:44.825 --> 11:48.332
‐ You know what?
So why don't you
take these pages?

11:48.332 --> 11:49.585
Go type them
into the computer‐‐

11:49.585 --> 11:51.839
‐ Nope, no, no,
I want to hear them.

12:02.569 --> 12:04.615
‐ Um...

12:04.615 --> 12:06.786
"When..."
[sniffs]

12:06.786 --> 12:09.248
[stammers]

12:09.248 --> 12:11.086
Um, Mc...

12:11.086 --> 12:14.593
"When he...

12:14.593 --> 12:16.722
"When Mc...

12:16.722 --> 12:18.518
"When he," uh‐‐

12:18.518 --> 12:21.439
"When he sure‐‐when he's..."

12:21.439 --> 12:22.901
[sighs]

12:22.901 --> 12:25.573
Sorry.
"When he super...

12:25.573 --> 12:29.957
[stammers]
"Seized them from the...

12:31.459 --> 12:33.756
Act, he..."

12:33.756 --> 12:36.469
<i>CARL: You make her nervous.</i>
<i>She's fine with me.</i>

12:36.469 --> 12:38.683
CRYSILDA:
She is not getting any better.

12:38.683 --> 12:41.772
‐ I'm with her
every goddamn day...

12:41.772 --> 12:43.776
‐ Okay, you watch your mouth.

12:43.776 --> 12:47.450
‐ And I can tell you
that she is getting better.

12:47.450 --> 12:51.249
‐ You are here every day
because you don't have a job.

12:51.249 --> 12:52.836
‐ I work.

12:52.836 --> 12:55.800
‐ You pack garlic
in boxes at night.

12:55.800 --> 12:57.053
That's not working.

12:57.053 --> 12:58.765
‐ I write better
in the morning.

12:58.765 --> 13:01.520
‐ Oh, okay, of course.
It's all about you.

13:01.520 --> 13:04.568
I have a real job.
I run this house.

13:04.568 --> 13:07.657
I clean your filth,
and for what?

13:07.657 --> 13:09.953
So you can read our daughter
dirty bits

13:09.953 --> 13:11.206
or make her read them to you?

13:11.206 --> 13:13.335
‐ They're not dirty.
It's historical fiction!

13:13.335 --> 13:16.842
‐ It is twaddle, is what it is!
‐ "Twaddle."

13:16.842 --> 13:18.428
CRYSILDA:
You had ten years, Carl.

13:18.428 --> 13:21.101
Ten!
It is not happening!

13:21.101 --> 13:22.687
CARL:
Don't you tell me what I'm not!

13:22.687 --> 13:24.357
‐ You couldn't
finish school, Carl!

13:24.357 --> 13:26.319
Expect me to believe
you're gonna finish a book?

13:26.319 --> 13:29.117
Ugh!

13:29.117 --> 13:32.707
[computer whirring softly]

13:32.707 --> 13:34.545
[keyboard clacking]

13:36.172 --> 13:37.926
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

13:37.926 --> 13:40.974
CARL:
Gotta get just the right angle
or you'll be on the banker.

13:43.186 --> 13:44.731
ANNIE:
[grunts]

13:44.731 --> 13:48.446
‐ Oh, dude.
[laughing]

13:48.446 --> 13:51.327
Oh, my daughter's killing me!

13:51.327 --> 13:53.206
Oh!

13:53.206 --> 13:55.587
<i>ANNIE:</i>
<i>[muffled speech]</i>

13:55.587 --> 13:56.964
<i>CARL: No, I'm winning.</i>
<i>ANNIE: Oh, okay.</i>

13:56.964 --> 13:58.593
<i>[laughs]</i>
<i>What?</i>

13:58.593 --> 14:01.599
[indistinct chatter]

14:03.143 --> 14:06.107
‐ Listen, I'm gonna be
staying with you from now on.

14:06.107 --> 14:08.863
[dental tool clacks]
[sighs]

14:08.863 --> 14:12.119
I'm only taking weekend shifts
at Dr. Nixon's,

14:12.119 --> 14:16.085
and your dad is getting
his old job back at the bank.

14:16.085 --> 14:20.010
‐ But Daddy teaches me fine.
‐ He does not teach you at all.

14:20.010 --> 14:21.555
It's always recess
with you two.

14:21.555 --> 14:24.561
Open.
[sighs]

14:24.561 --> 14:26.439
[tool clacking]

14:26.439 --> 14:30.489
What I want for you is more...

14:30.489 --> 14:33.621
Than this filthy place.

14:33.621 --> 14:36.585
You are much better than this.

14:36.585 --> 14:39.465
‐ I am?

14:39.465 --> 14:42.764
‐ Oh, honey, of course you are.

14:42.764 --> 14:46.145
Don't let anybody
mix you up about it.

14:46.145 --> 14:49.820
[sighs]
Forget Daddy's silly book.

14:49.820 --> 14:51.406
<i>[pop music</i>
<i>playing over radio]</i>

14:51.406 --> 14:53.493
Focus on that GED.

14:53.493 --> 14:57.126
You get it,
and you get out of this place.

14:57.126 --> 14:59.589
You wanna end up like your mom?
[laughs]

14:59.589 --> 15:03.054
Wearing these jammies?
‐ Mom, I like your uniform.

15:05.977 --> 15:08.106
CRYSILDA:
[sighs]

15:08.106 --> 15:10.318
Get the white coat.

15:10.318 --> 15:13.659
That's the uniform
folks salute.

15:13.659 --> 15:16.330
Girls who wear these,
we just clean.

15:16.330 --> 15:18.126
[chuckles]

15:18.126 --> 15:20.840
Nothing on Earth dirtier
than the human mouth, Annie.

15:20.840 --> 15:24.263
You clean and clean...
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

15:24.263 --> 15:26.894
and it just gets dirty again.

15:26.894 --> 15:29.023
‐ [grunts softly]
Ow!

15:32.947 --> 15:36.914
‐ Your dad has been letting you
eat candy again, hasn't he?

15:36.914 --> 15:40.838
‐ Only when
we finish a chapter.

15:40.838 --> 15:44.386
‐ Watch those molars.

15:44.386 --> 15:47.519
<i>The rot creeps from the back.</i>

15:47.519 --> 15:51.568
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:51.568 --> 15:54.533
[crickets chirping]

16:04.301 --> 16:06.013
[knocking on door]

16:06.013 --> 16:09.478
‐ Come in.

16:09.478 --> 16:10.982
‐ I have to go somewhere.

16:10.982 --> 16:13.612
‐ Yeah, o‐okay.
Uh, I'll be fine.

16:13.612 --> 16:15.031
‐ Yeah.

16:15.031 --> 16:22.045
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:28.684 --> 16:30.270
ABDI:
Hey, how are we doing?

16:30.270 --> 16:33.694
‐ Well.
Thanks for coming down.
Let me show you this.

16:33.694 --> 16:35.531
ABDI:
Will it be ready for tomorrow?

16:35.531 --> 16:37.451
ABDI'S GUY: Yeah, yeah.

16:37.451 --> 16:40.457
<i>[sinister music]</i>

16:40.457 --> 16:42.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:42.336 --> 16:45.300
ANNIE: [breathing heavily]

16:55.320 --> 16:56.990
<i>JOY:</i>
<i>I told Abdi five minutes,</i>

16:56.990 --> 16:59.245
and we're done
when I say we're done.

16:59.245 --> 17:02.251
[insects chirping]

17:04.547 --> 17:07.595
‐ First,

17:07.595 --> 17:09.516
I would never hurt you.

17:12.437 --> 17:16.112
What happened at the lodge...

17:16.112 --> 17:18.993
I hit a bad patch.

17:18.993 --> 17:22.165
But I'm through it now,

17:22.165 --> 17:24.921
and I'll be even better
when we leave this place.

17:24.921 --> 17:27.050
JOY: You‐‐you need
to talk to someone.

17:27.050 --> 17:29.221
‐ If I put my head

17:29.221 --> 17:32.729
in the hands of those doctors,

17:32.729 --> 17:36.862
that means I put you
in their hands too.

17:36.862 --> 17:39.074
And I have seen enough
of that world

17:39.074 --> 17:41.913
to know that
they cannot be trusted, Joy.

17:41.913 --> 17:44.209
JOY: You checked yourself in
when we were in Missouri

17:44.209 --> 17:46.130
and you got better.

17:46.130 --> 17:48.134
‐ I'm‐‐

17:48.134 --> 17:50.055
I am your mother.

17:50.055 --> 17:52.309
Now, I don't need
to prove anything.

17:54.271 --> 17:55.733
‐ What's his name?

17:55.733 --> 17:57.486
‐ Who?

17:57.486 --> 17:59.448
‐ Dad.

18:01.620 --> 18:04.166
‐ The less you know,
the safer you are.

18:06.045 --> 18:08.967
‐ I don't believe that anymore.
‐ He's a bad man.

18:08.967 --> 18:11.848
JOY: [laughs softly]
That's not enough.

18:11.848 --> 18:14.269
‐ It's not a nice story, Joy.

18:14.269 --> 18:16.608
JOY: Tell me anyways.
I‐‐I'm a grown‐up.

18:16.608 --> 18:19.238
‐ No, you're not.
JOY: Tell me.

18:22.327 --> 18:26.210
We're‐‐we're done.
Get out or‐‐or I'll scream.

18:30.594 --> 18:33.224
‐ Little love...

18:33.224 --> 18:35.855
[door opens]

18:35.855 --> 18:39.236
ABDI: You okay in there?
‐ It's fine. She's leaving.

18:39.236 --> 18:41.950
<i>[uneasy violin music]</i>

18:41.950 --> 18:43.912
ABDI: Get out.

18:43.912 --> 18:46.918
Let's go.

18:46.918 --> 18:48.463
Come on.

18:50.551 --> 18:52.179
[door slams]

18:53.891 --> 18:57.105
<i>ANNIE: [stammering]</i>
<i>"'There are two kinds...</i>

18:57.105 --> 19:00.738
<i>"'of people...</i>

19:00.738 --> 19:05.121
"'in this world, Annabel,'

19:05.121 --> 19:08.336
"Prester Jack said.

19:08.336 --> 19:12.385
'There are soldiers
and settlers.'"

19:13.722 --> 19:15.559
‐ Hello.

19:15.559 --> 19:18.565
[approaching footsteps]

19:21.320 --> 19:23.491
I'm Rita.

19:25.119 --> 19:27.625
‐ Annie, can you say hello?

19:27.625 --> 19:29.838
Annie, we talked about this.

19:29.838 --> 19:33.386
Your dad is not
a professional‐‐at anything...

19:33.386 --> 19:35.265
BOTH: [laugh]

19:37.520 --> 19:40.275
Fact is, little love,
you need some special help

19:40.275 --> 19:44.032
before this big GED next year,
and Rita is it.

19:44.032 --> 19:45.953
‐ Maybe Annie and I
could have a moment,

19:45.953 --> 19:47.748
get to know each other.

19:47.748 --> 19:49.586
‐ Oh.

19:49.586 --> 19:51.005
Well, uh‐‐

19:51.005 --> 19:52.800
‐ Cool, thanks.

19:54.679 --> 19:56.725
‐ Cool.
[laughs awkwardly]

19:59.021 --> 20:02.027
[retreating footsteps]

20:05.618 --> 20:08.999
RITA:
So, what do you like to read?

20:08.999 --> 20:11.337
‐ My dad's book, mostly.

20:11.337 --> 20:13.884
‐ Is this it?

20:13.884 --> 20:16.723
‐ You can't just
start in the middle.

20:16.723 --> 20:18.351
It's a really big story.

20:20.940 --> 20:23.069
‐ Your mom says
you help him tell it.

20:23.069 --> 20:26.200
‐ Um, no, I‐‐not really.

20:26.200 --> 20:28.371
Um, I mean,

20:28.371 --> 20:32.087
sometimes he loses his place
and forgets where he left off,

20:32.087 --> 20:34.884
so I just make sure
that things match up.

20:34.884 --> 20:38.349
I'm not very good at reading,
but I can understand stories.

20:40.562 --> 20:42.984
‐ [clicks tongue]

20:42.984 --> 20:45.656
Are you a fan of this one?

20:47.033 --> 20:49.413
‐ That's a kid's book.
RITA: Not really.

20:49.413 --> 20:51.333
Not the real story.

20:54.757 --> 20:57.930
This isn't like the cartoon.

20:57.930 --> 20:59.809
In the original,
they burn his feet off,

20:59.809 --> 21:01.646
and that's just the beginning.

21:01.646 --> 21:04.109
‐ 'Cause he lies?
‐ That's right.

21:05.486 --> 21:08.367
‐ So the lying part's the same,
but there's just consequences.

21:08.367 --> 21:11.750
I always tell my dad
with his stories
there has to be consequences

21:11.750 --> 21:13.920
or else it's just
a bunch of stuff happening,

21:13.920 --> 21:16.467
and that's not a real story,
I don't think.

21:16.467 --> 21:20.684
‐ Well, maybe there's more than
one writer in this family.

21:20.684 --> 21:21.895
‐ [laughs softly]

21:21.895 --> 21:24.859
‐ Pro...
"Prah"...

21:24.859 --> 21:26.654
ANNIE: Prah...
RITA: Prah...

21:26.654 --> 21:28.617
It's not working!

21:28.617 --> 21:31.623
‐ Slow it down
and sound it out.

21:31.623 --> 21:33.459
<i>[nostalgic piano music]</i>

21:33.459 --> 21:35.046
‐ "Boys."

21:35.046 --> 21:38.094
Um, "boys all"...

21:38.094 --> 21:40.891
[stammering]

21:40.891 --> 21:43.145
‐ Just take a breath.
[exhales]

21:43.145 --> 21:45.316
Breathe in.
[inhales]

21:45.316 --> 21:47.988
Breathe out.
[exhales]

21:47.988 --> 21:51.245
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:51.245 --> 21:54.794
You feel okay?

21:54.794 --> 21:56.213
Mm‐kay, let's try it again.

21:56.213 --> 21:57.967
‐ This is where
my daddy writes his book.

21:57.967 --> 22:00.806
‐ Oh, that's so nice.

22:00.806 --> 22:02.893
‐ This is pretty much
where he works.

22:02.893 --> 22:05.691
RITA: Do you, um‐‐
do you have your book?

22:05.691 --> 22:08.154
‐ "Pinocchio said to himself
with great content,

22:08.154 --> 22:11.410
"'How ridiculous I was

22:11.410 --> 22:13.414
"as a...'"
[stammering]

22:13.414 --> 22:15.544
"'Marionette,

22:15.544 --> 22:19.301
"'and how happy I am

22:19.301 --> 22:22.182
now that I've become
a real boy.'"

22:22.182 --> 22:28.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:28.444 --> 22:31.701
So he just turns
into a real boy?

22:33.914 --> 22:37.880
‐ Yes, it's his redemption.

22:37.880 --> 22:40.510
Do you remember that word?
‐ Yeah, I‐‐I know the word.

22:40.510 --> 22:44.644
Um, but what's it doing
at the end of this story?

22:44.644 --> 22:48.025
‐ I‐‐I don't understand.
‐ Well, Pinocchio's a liar,

22:48.025 --> 22:50.739
so why should
he get a happy ending?

22:50.739 --> 22:52.826
Just because
he gave a fairy some coins?

22:52.826 --> 22:55.999
That's not how it works.
‐ Well, how should it work?

22:55.999 --> 22:58.003
‐ Well, they should have
killed him.

23:02.888 --> 23:06.186
[door slams]
‐ Funny thing is, is they did.

23:06.186 --> 23:09.234
In Collodi's first draft,
that was the ending.

23:09.234 --> 23:11.488
‐ Well, there you go.
Now, why the heck
did he change it?

23:11.488 --> 23:13.325
RITA:
'Cause his editor thought
it was too dark.

23:13.325 --> 23:15.037
He thought it would scare kids.

23:15.037 --> 23:16.749
‐ Well, sure,
they should be scared!

23:16.749 --> 23:19.630
In this world,
you're either good
or you're bad, and‐‐

23:19.630 --> 23:21.258
and if you're bad, you pay.

23:21.258 --> 23:24.431
‐ Annie, did your mom
tell you that?

23:24.431 --> 23:27.478
‐ I'm sorry, I was‐‐
could we have a conversation?

23:27.478 --> 23:29.107
Could we have
a quick, uh, word?

23:29.107 --> 23:32.071
‐ Sure.
Uh, why don't you
go take a break?

23:32.071 --> 23:34.535
‐ [sighs]

23:43.093 --> 23:44.972
You know...
RITA: Mr. Wilkes,
before you start‐‐

23:44.972 --> 23:46.224
‐ I'm‐‐I'm not a professional,

23:46.224 --> 23:48.312
but you've got her
reading toddlers' books.

23:48.312 --> 23:49.690
I don't know how
that's supposed to help her.

23:49.690 --> 23:51.986
‐ Annie is intelligent...
‐ Yes, she is, I know that.

23:51.986 --> 23:54.992
‐ She's probably skipped
a few developmental steps
early on, and that's‐‐

23:54.992 --> 23:56.704
‐ Let me, um‐‐
let me tell you something

23:56.704 --> 23:58.457
about how
my daughter's brain works‐‐

23:58.457 --> 24:02.674
‐ Mr. Wilkes, I'm gonna ask you
not to interrupt me.

24:02.674 --> 24:04.929
You posed a question
and I'm trying to answer you,

24:04.929 --> 24:07.726
but you have to let me, okay?

24:07.726 --> 24:09.563
Okay.

24:11.943 --> 24:14.824
Your daughter is smart.
Very smart.

24:14.824 --> 24:19.332
She can't grow as a reader
just reading you.

24:19.332 --> 24:21.294
You're her father.

24:21.294 --> 24:23.424
You loom large.

24:23.424 --> 24:26.514
All this, this has promise.

24:26.514 --> 24:29.854
Uh, "settlers and searchers."

24:29.854 --> 24:33.235
That's beautiful.

24:33.235 --> 24:36.909
But it's your story, not hers.

24:36.909 --> 24:38.872
<i>[soft dramatic music]</i>

24:38.872 --> 24:42.754
You have to let her
write her own.

24:42.754 --> 24:45.886
‐ [clears throat]
You‐‐you like that?

24:45.886 --> 24:49.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:49.852 --> 24:51.772
‐ I'm sorry, uh‐‐

24:51.772 --> 24:53.526
well, yes, I‐‐I do.

24:53.526 --> 24:55.614
It's very good.
CARL: [laughs softly]

24:55.614 --> 24:57.283
Uh, thank you.

24:57.283 --> 25:00.414
I've been a writer, uh,
since a very young age.

25:00.414 --> 25:03.128
RITA: Oh, I‐‐I know.
Annie told me all about you.

25:03.128 --> 25:06.844
‐ Uh, lots of‐‐
lots of other things
that I've written too.

25:06.844 --> 25:09.683
‐ I bet.
CARL: I have some
earlier drafts.

25:09.683 --> 25:12.313
<i>I‐‐I love to hear her read it,</i>
<i>which is why I‐‐</i>

25:12.313 --> 25:15.779
<i>why I continue to feed her</i>
<i>those pages one at a time.</i>

25:15.779 --> 25:17.490
ANNIE: Even‐‐
‐ Evidence.

25:17.490 --> 25:18.993
‐ Evidence.
‐ Evidence.

25:18.993 --> 25:23.460
‐ Now this one's a tricky one
because it looks like "bus."

25:23.460 --> 25:24.755
Some...
ANNIE: Some...

25:24.755 --> 25:26.759
‐ Ah...
ANNIE: Some, uh‐‐

25:26.759 --> 25:28.555
BOTH: Ah...

25:28.555 --> 25:30.474
‐ Sum‐ma...

25:30.474 --> 25:33.230
[laughter]

25:33.230 --> 25:35.569
‐ Remember with the "I."
[indistinct chatter]

25:35.569 --> 25:37.446
[both trilling lips]
Okay, shake it out.

25:37.446 --> 25:39.785
[both babbling]

25:39.785 --> 25:41.956
Just let it all go.
[laughs]

25:41.956 --> 25:44.962
‐ Okay.
But that's an E.

25:44.962 --> 25:46.716
‐ Around your neck.

25:46.716 --> 25:49.178
[grunts]
‐ Like this one?

25:49.178 --> 25:52.143
RITA: Mm‐hmm, yeah.

25:52.143 --> 25:54.230
BOTH: [laugh]

25:54.230 --> 25:57.278
<i>[rousing music]</i>

25:57.278 --> 26:04.292
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:04.292 --> 26:05.712
‐ And out.

26:05.712 --> 26:08.008
‐ [exhales]

26:08.008 --> 26:15.022
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:16.817 --> 26:18.278
"Shameless."

26:18.278 --> 26:20.449
<i>Marionette!</i>
[muttering]

26:29.718 --> 26:36.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:39.404 --> 26:42.118
[indistinct chatter]

26:42.118 --> 26:43.746
CHILD:
Come on, hurry up.

26:43.746 --> 26:45.416
[overlapping chatter]
CHILD: So good.

26:45.416 --> 26:47.294
CHILD: Trick or treat.

26:48.506 --> 26:51.344
‐ "Opposition.
Opposition.

26:51.344 --> 26:53.098
"Oppositional.

26:53.098 --> 26:56.312
Inter‐‐interpretation."

26:56.312 --> 27:00.070
Did you ever hear why
Mom and Dad took me out
of regular school?

27:04.412 --> 27:06.249
‐ That was a long time ago.

27:06.249 --> 27:10.717
‐ Well, they‐‐they didn't
let me go back, so...

27:10.717 --> 27:14.892
I guess that means
I didn't get better.

27:14.892 --> 27:18.148
‐ Annie,
none of that matters now.

27:18.148 --> 27:21.488
The only thing that matters
is that in less than a month,

27:21.488 --> 27:23.826
you're gonna pass this test.

27:25.622 --> 27:27.291
‐ Well, then
who will you teach?

27:35.182 --> 27:37.186
‐ This little one, I guess.

27:44.701 --> 27:46.287
ANNIE: [exhales]

27:52.592 --> 27:55.180
Oh, I can't wait to meet her.

27:59.313 --> 28:01.359
Where's her daddy?

28:03.990 --> 28:06.579
‐ It's, um...

28:08.498 --> 28:10.252
It's complicated.

28:12.924 --> 28:15.722
He's complicated.

28:15.722 --> 28:17.684
‐ No, it isn't.

28:17.684 --> 28:20.147
He's either a good man
or he isn't.

28:21.567 --> 28:24.280
‐ Annie,
nothing is that simple.

28:24.280 --> 28:26.409
‐ Well, you're good.

28:28.163 --> 28:30.208
And that's simple.

28:37.097 --> 28:39.393
[book pages rustling]

28:39.393 --> 28:43.193
Look what I learned.

28:43.193 --> 28:46.282
Are they, uh...
[mumbles indistinctly]

28:46.282 --> 28:49.080
Mom?

28:49.080 --> 28:50.332
Are you...
‐ Yeah?

28:50.332 --> 28:52.378
ANNIE: Are‐‐are you okay?

28:52.378 --> 28:55.258
<i>[music playing softly</i>
<i>over radio]</i>

28:55.258 --> 28:57.972
‐ You poor thing.

28:57.972 --> 28:59.851
‐ You don't think I'll pass?

28:59.851 --> 29:02.231
‐ Oh, you'll pass.

29:02.231 --> 29:06.072
You'll pass and pass
and that'll be enough.

29:06.072 --> 29:08.619
Mm.
‐ What's wrong?

29:08.619 --> 29:12.501
‐ Just getting by.

29:12.501 --> 29:14.548
‐ "Yeah, that'll be enough,"
they'll say.

29:14.548 --> 29:17.136
‐ Who‐‐who will say?

29:17.136 --> 29:19.473
‐ Dirty birds

29:19.473 --> 29:21.645
who want you close
and low to the ground

29:21.645 --> 29:23.398
so they can snatch
what they want

29:23.398 --> 29:25.528
whenever they want it,

29:25.528 --> 29:29.160
just like your father did to me
when I was barely a woman.

29:29.160 --> 29:32.166
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:32.166 --> 29:33.794
[clicks tongue]

29:33.794 --> 29:36.800
<i>[tense music fades,</i>
<i>music on radio continues]</i>

29:36.800 --> 29:43.021
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:43.021 --> 29:45.150
[bottle slides, clunks]

29:45.150 --> 29:50.368
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:50.368 --> 29:53.374
<i>ANNIE: "After the last dirt</i>
<i>was dropped on the coffin,</i>

29:53.374 --> 29:55.337
Prester Jack threw
the shovel in after it."

29:55.337 --> 29:57.424
CARL:
Rita's taught you so well.

29:57.424 --> 30:00.138
ANNIE: "And then he took
Annabel's hand

30:00.138 --> 30:02.100
"and they walked away
from the grave

30:02.100 --> 30:04.438
"and towards the sun

30:04.438 --> 30:07.277
and a horizon they'd hoped
they'd never find."

30:07.277 --> 30:09.156
‐ Do you like it?

30:10.993 --> 30:13.707
‐ [laughs]
I love it.

30:13.707 --> 30:16.630
CARL: [sighs]
‐ [laughs]

30:16.630 --> 30:19.594
‐ Do you know
I got a publisher interested?

30:19.594 --> 30:21.138
‐ Daddy!

30:21.138 --> 30:23.059
‐ Well, I‐‐I mean, the fella
hasn't formally read it yet,

30:23.059 --> 30:25.021
but I met him in the bank
the other day

30:25.021 --> 30:27.652
and said I'd be finished soon
and he‐‐he can't wait.

30:27.652 --> 30:29.948
‐ He'll love it.
CARL: [chuckles]

30:31.577 --> 30:34.373
‐ You found it.
‐ What?

30:34.373 --> 30:37.254
‐ Your Laughing Place.

30:37.254 --> 30:39.425
‐ [laughs softly]

30:43.099 --> 30:45.395
Well, you know, that, um...

30:47.650 --> 30:50.656
That's the thing of it,
Annie‐bear.

30:50.656 --> 30:54.288
There's, um‐‐there's
something that I need
to talk to you about.

30:57.545 --> 30:59.925
I'm gonna be moving out.

31:03.599 --> 31:05.728
‐ Um,

31:05.728 --> 31:08.692
for how long?

31:08.692 --> 31:11.238
‐ A while.

31:11.238 --> 31:13.451
I need‐‐

31:13.451 --> 31:18.336
I need to figure out
my place in this world.

31:20.423 --> 31:22.052
‐ [sniffles]
Like Prester Jack?

31:22.052 --> 31:25.016
‐ [laughs softly]

31:25.016 --> 31:26.435
Well, actually, maybe‐‐

31:26.435 --> 31:29.066
maybe a little bit more
like Annabel.

31:29.066 --> 31:31.070
You know, she, um‐‐

31:31.070 --> 31:33.408
in the end,
Jack is a settler...

31:33.408 --> 31:34.619
‐ [sniffles]

31:34.619 --> 31:37.290
‐ But Annabel,
she'll never stop looking,

31:37.290 --> 31:41.007
and that‐‐and that‐‐
that's me, darling.

31:41.007 --> 31:42.760
‐ Well, what are you
looking for?

31:47.269 --> 31:49.816
[weeping softly]

31:49.816 --> 31:51.027
‐ I‐‐I don't know.

31:51.027 --> 31:52.613
